  "text": "Envoy uses a comprehensive multi-layered approach to prevent HTTP request header injection attacks. The validation occurs at multiple levels:\n\n**Header Validation Logic (source/common/http/header_utility.cc/.h):**\n- `headerNameIsValid()`: Validates header names against RFC 7230 character sets, checking for valid token characters. Uses character tables from character_set_validation.h. For pseudo-headers (starting with ':'), delegates to nghttp2 or quiche validation.\n- `headerValueIsValid()`: Validates header values using http2::adapter::HeaderValidator, allowing obsolete text per RFC.\n- `checkValidRequestHeaders()`: Performs comprehensive validation of all header entries in a request, checking both names and values for forbidden characters (embedded NULLs, newlines, etc.).\n- `requestHeadersValid()`: Validates specific headers (Host, Method, Scheme) for authority compliance and proper formatting.\n- `isRemovableHeader()` / `isModifiableHeader()`: Prevents removal/modification of pseudo-headers (starting with ':') and the Host header, which are critical for HTTP semantics.\n\n**Internal Header Stripping (source/common/http/conn_manager_utility.cc/.h):**\n- `cleanInternalHeaders()`: Strips internal-only headers from edge requests and external requests. Removes envoy-prefixed headers (EnvoyDecoratorOperation, EnvoyDownstreamServiceCluster, etc.) that could be injected by untrusted clients.\n- `sanitizeTEHeader()`: Sanitizes the TE (Transfer-Encoding) header to only allow the 'trailers' value, preventing header injection through this vector.\n\n**Connection Header Sanitization (source/common/http/utility.cc):**\n- `sanitizeConnectionHeader()`: Prevents header injection via the Connection header, which nominates other headers for removal. Enforces a maximum of 10 nominated headers, rejects attempts to nominate pseudo-headers or X-Forwarded-* headers, and validates the TE header size.\n\n**Character Set Validation (source/common/http/character_set_validation.h):**\n- Provides bit-table lookup functions and character set tables (kGenericHeaderNameCharTable, kUriQueryAndFragmentCharTable) compliant with RFC 9110 for efficient header name/value character validation.\n\n**Header Validator Extension (source/extensions/http/header_validators/envoy_default/):**\n- Base HeaderValidator class and protocol-specific implementations (http1_header_validator.cc, http2_header_validator.cc) provide extensible header validation.\n- Validates method, status, path, host, scheme, content-length headers against protocol-specific rules.\n- `sanitizeHeadersWithUnderscores()`: Handles headers with underscores based on configuration (ALLOW, DROP_HEADER, or REJECT).\n- Path normalization and percent-encoded sequence checking prevent URL-based injection attacks.\n\n**HTTP/1 and HTTP/2 Codec Integration (source/common/http/http1/codec_impl.cc, http2/codec_impl.cc):**\n- Both HTTP/1 and HTTP/2 codecs call HeaderUtility::checkValidRequestHeaders() to validate headers at parsing time.\n- HTTP/1 codec uses Balsa parser (balsa_parser.cc) with validation policies to reject invalid header characters in responses.\n- HTTP/2 codec integrates nghttp2 header validation to ensure RFC 9113 compliance.\n\n**Connection Manager Integration (source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc):**\n- `validateHeaders()`: Calls header_validator_->validateRequestHeaders() to apply header validation rules.\n- `mutateRequestHeaders()` in ConnectionManagerUtility: Applies all header mutations including sanitization, internal header removal, and port stripping.\n- Headers are validated on first pass only (is_internally_created check) to prevent bypass for internally-generated requests.\n\n**Pseudo-Header Protection:**\n- Pseudo-headers (HTTP/2 headers starting with ':') are protected from removal and modification through isRemovableHeader() and isModifiableHeader() checks.\n- These include :authority, :method, :path, :scheme, and :status headers critical to request/response semantics.\n\nTogether, these components create defense-in-depth against HTTP header injection by validating character sets, preventing internal header injection, sanitizing dangerous headers, and protecting pseudo-headers from manipulation."
}
